[3] Viet Nam
Date: Wed 6 Aug 2014
Source: Tuoitre News [edited]
http://tuoitrenews.vn/society/21498/encephalitis-meningitis-rage-in-vietnams-son-la-province-killing-13-kids


Encephalitis and meningitis have spread to most areas of the northern province of Son La, affecting more than 100 children and killing 13 of them so far this year [2014], health authorities reported on Tuesday [5 Aug 2014].

Currently, the provincial capital Son La City and 10 out of the 11 districts of the province have been stricken by the 2 diseases, the provincial Health Department said.

Nguyen Tran Hien, director of the Hanoi-based Central Institute of Hygiene and Epidemiology, said that health experts have taken samples from 73 of the more than 100 child patients for testing, and 31 of them were positive for Japanese encephalitis (JE) [virus? antibody?]. Of these 31 kids, 3 had been vaccinated against JE [virus], Hien added.

Chu warned that JE symptoms include high fever, headache, feeling sick, vomiting, seizures, conscious disorder, and coma. JE virus is the leading cause of vaccine-preventable encephalitis in Asia and the Western Pacific, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said.

In preventing JE, the National Extended Vaccination Program and the local Health Department have decided to vaccinate all the children under 15 that have yet to receive vaccination against the 2 diseases in the province, Hien said.

When asked why many children have now contracted the deadly disease despite the provincial health authorities launching a vaccination drive against JE in 2007, Hien explained that, in that year, only 50 percent of local children were given vaccination due to a shortage of vaccine shots.

[The 2 Jul 2014 edition of Tuoitre News (http://tuoitrenews.vn/society/20720/viral-encephalitis-affects-325-people-kills-5-in-vietnam) reported that viral encephalitis had spread to 31 provinces and cities in Viet Nam, affecting 325 people and killing 5 of them in the 1st 6 months of this year [2014], health authorities said. - Mod.TY]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Unfortunately, the above report does not indicate what proportions of the more than 100 cases are due to JE virus infections and to meningitis. However, the sample of 73 cases laboratory tested indicated that 42 per cent were due to JE virus infections. This is not surprising, since Viet Nam has had active JE virus transmission this year (2014). Most cases of Japanese encephalitis there occur in the south during the rainy and early dry season, shifting to the north of the country during late summer and autumn. Nationally, 73 per cent of the population lives in areas of risk to JE virus infection.

Wild birds, especially ardeids, are reservoirs of JEV. Pigs are amplifying hosts. Several _Culex_ mosquito species are efficient vectors of the virus, transmitting the virus among wild birds and pigs and to humans. Vaccination and avoidance of mosquito bites are the only measures available to avoid infection and disease.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Viet Nam can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2669178,152. - Mod.TY]
